Bayesian approach to traffic incident prediction¶

Adam Filapek, Łukasz Faruga

1. Introduction¶

  • 1.19 million road traffic fatalities worldwide (WHO)
  • 7th leading cause of death by 2030
  • est. cost $US 1.8 trillion 2015-30 globally

Various approaches:

  • neural networks
  • random forests
  • gradient boosting

2. Our project¶

This project focuses on developing a Bayesian model to predict traffic incident counts based on weather data. Our objective is to generate monthly predictions at the voivodeship level in Poland.

3. Models¶

The first model was based solely on humidity $$ y \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda) $$ $$ \lambda = a \cdot h $$ $$ a \sim \text{HalfNormal}(\mu_{a}, \sigma_{a})$$

while the second one addded temperature and a constant. $$ y \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda) $$ $$ \lambda = a \cdot h + b \cdot t + c$$ $$ a \sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{a}, \sigma_{a})$$ $$ b \sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{b}, \sigma_{b})$$ $$ c \sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{c}, \sigma_{c})$$

Priors¶

First model¶

$$a \sim \text{HalfNormal}(0, 68) $$

Second model¶

$$ a \sim \text{Normal}(0, 68)$$ $$ b \sim \text{Normal}(0, 680)$$ $$ c \sim \text{Normal}(2000, 1000)$$
